<p>If you are a Christmas period lover you might be also fond of the typical Christmas markets. North of the Alps, the so called Christkindlmarkts (in German the equivalent of Christ Child Market) take place every year during the four weeks of Advent and bustle the main squares of the cities and the neighbouring pedestrian areas with their traditional stalls. The first documents mentioning these peculiar and joyful December markets date back to the Late Middle Age and interest most of the cities belonging to the former Holy Roman Empire (the first in Vienna was held in 1294, in Munich and in Bautzen around 1310, then Dresden in 1434 and Augsburg in 1498). As far as Italy is concerned, the most famous Christmas markets take place in the German-speaking areas and mainly in South Tirol cities such as Bolzano, Merano, Brixen, Sterzing and Bruneck. <br>A special exception in Northern Italy is represented by Milan, where the citizens celebrate their patron, Saint Ambrose, (339-397 AD) on 7th December. The anniversary is immediately followed by the feast of the Immaculate Conception (on 8th December) and in the Ambrosian Dioceses it is a perfect period to take a short break from daily activities. Often you might have the chance of a long week-end which can either be spent by the Milanese on the nearby mountains to enjoy the first snow, or remaining in town in the warm, friendly atmosphere, which animates the “Oh bej! Oh bej!” fair.</p>

